<DOC><DOCNO> AP890801-0198 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2232EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0780 08-01 0523</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostages-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0534</SECOND><HEAD>Hostage Developments at a Glance</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf in `U.S. Reaction' section to UPDATE with messageto Iran.</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Tuesday's hostage developments at a glance:</TEXT><HEAD>DEADLINES AND DENIALS</HEAD><TEXT>   The group holding American hostage Joseph Cicippio said it hadextended by 48 hours the deadline for his ``execution.'' TheRevolutionary Justice Organization issued a statement saying thedeadline of 6 p.m. Tuesday (11 a.m. EDT) was extended due to``friendly appeals and sincere behests as well as some specialfactors and the moving plea by Cicippio's wife.''   The group had said Monday that Cicippio would be killed unlessIsrael freed captured Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid. The statement issuedTuesday said there would be no further postponement of the deadline.   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, which on Monday saidit had hanged U.S. Lt. Col. William R. Higgins in retaliation forObeid's abduction, denied Tuesday that it had made telephone callsthreatening to kill Anglican church envoy Terry Waite, whodisappeared in January 1987.</TEXT><HEAD>HOSTAGE RELATIVES</HEAD><TEXT>   Cicippio's wife, Ilham, made her plea during a news conferencein Beirut. She urged her husband's kidnappers to give him a chance``to prove to you that he is innocent of all guilt.'' Her husband,who converted to Islam in 1985, was kidnapped Sept. 12, 1986, whileworking for the American University in Beirut.   In Cicippio's home town of Norristown, Pa., his relativesreacted with caution to his two-day reprieve, and said they hopedhis captors would free him.   In Washington, Higgins' wife, Robin, viewed the videotape of thepurported execution of her husband, and said it was impossible tomake a definite determination of whether he was dead or alive. Shecalled on the captors to ``give us proof.''</TEXT><HEAD>U.S. REACTION</HEAD><TEXT>   President Bush met for a second day with senior advisers. Oneadministration source said military action was possible, butanother official said a hostage rescue or a military strike were``not attractive options.''   Officials said the United States sent a strongly worded messageto Iran on behalf of the hostages. The administration also appealedto Saudi Arabia and other Arab governments as well as the SovietUnion for help in winning the release of all American captives inLebanon. Bush telephoned the Pope and the prime minister of Turkey,and a spokesman said Bush planned to ``talk to a lot of people,involve a lot of people'' to help the hostages.</TEXT><HEAD>ISRAEL</HEAD><TEXT>   Israel insisted it would not free Obeid despite the reportedkilling of Higgins and the threats against other hostages. Butofficials said Israel remained willing to exchange Obeid and otherLebanese Shiite prisoners for Israeli soldiers and Westernhostages. The radical Shiite group Hezbollah, of which Obeid is aspiritual leader, rejected the deal.   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir expressed ``deep sorrow'' overHiggins' reported death. A Foreign Ministry spokesman called on``the American people not to allow this outrage to drive a wedgebetween the United States and Israel.'' In Washington, debatecontinued on Capitol Hill about the wisdom of the Israeli decisionto kidnap Obeid.</TEXT></DOC>